A class-based GJS component uses `@tracked` for reactive state and embeds `<template>` inside the class body.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class RunCounter extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;

  @action
  addRun() {
    this.runs += 1;
  }

  <template>
    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 p-4 bg-white rounded shadow">
      <span class="text-3xl font-bold text-green-700">{{this.runs}}</span>
      <button
        type="button"
        class="px-4 py-2 bg-green-600 text-white rounded hover:bg-green-700"
        {{on "click" this.addRun}}
      >
        +1 Run
      </button>
    </div>
  </template>
}
```

The `@tracked` decorator makes `runs` reactive — the template re-renders automatically when it changes. The `@action` decorator binds `this` correctly in the event handler.

Use the `{{on}}` modifier to attach DOM event listeners in GJS templates.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class WicketTracker extends Component {
  @tracked wickets = 0;

  @action
  recordWicket() {
    if (this.wickets < 10) {
      this.wickets += 1;
    }
  }

  <template>
    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 p-4">
      <span class="text-2xl font-bold text-red-700">{{this.wickets}}/10</span>
      <button
        type="button"
        class="px-3 py-1.5 bg-red-600 text-white text-sm rounded hover:bg-red-700"
        {{on "click" this.recordWicket}}
      >
        Wicket 🎯
      </button>
    </div>
  </template>
}
```

`{{on "click" this.recordWicket}}` attaches a native click listener. The modifier handles cleanup automatically when the element is removed from the DOM.

Import the component at the top of your `.gjs` file and use it with angle bracket syntax in the template.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import PlayerCard from './player-card';
import ScoreBadge from './score-badge';

export default class TeamRoster extends Component {
  <template>
    <div class="space-y-2 p-4">
      {{#each @players as |player|}}
        <PlayerCard @name={{player.name}} @position={{player.position}}>
          <ScoreBadge @runs={{player.runs}} @balls={{player.balls}} />
        </PlayerCard>
      {{/each}}
    </div>
  </template>
}
```

Components must be imported before they can be used — GJS uses JavaScript module scope, so there's no global component registry. Angle bracket syntax (`<PlayerCard />`) is the only supported invocation style in Glimmer.

Pass data to child components using the `@argName={{value}}` syntax in the template.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import MatchCard from './match-card';

export default class MatchList extends Component {
  get featuredMatch() {
    return this.args.matches?.[0];
  }

  <template>
    <section class="space-y-4">
      {{#each @matches as |match|}}
        <MatchCard
          @title={{match.title}}
          @venue={{match.venue}}
          @date={{match.date}}
          @isLive={{match.isLive}}
          @homeScore={{match.homeScore}}
          @awayScore={{match.awayScore}}
        />
      {{/each}}
    </section>
  </template>
}
```

Args prefixed with `@` are the public API of a component. Inside the child, access them as `@title` in the template or `this.args.title` in the class. Always pass dynamic values with `={{expression}}` and static strings with `="value"`.

Define a plain function above the component class and use it directly in the template — no registration needed.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';

const formatOvers = (balls) => {
  const overs = Math.floor(balls / 6);
  const rem = balls % 6;
  return `${overs}.${rem}`;
};

const strikeRate = (runs, balls) => {
  if (!balls) return '0.00';
  return ((runs / balls) * 100).toFixed(2);
};

export default class BatsmanRow extends Component {
  <template>
    <tr class="border-b hover:bg-gray-50">
      <td class="p-2">{{@player.name}}</td>
      <td class="p-2 text-center font-bold">{{@player.runs}}</td>
      <td class="p-2 text-center">{{@player.balls}}</td>
      <td class="p-2 text-center text-gray-500">
        {{strikeRate @player.runs @player.balls}}
      </td>
    </tr>
  </template>
}
```

Local helpers are just JavaScript functions in scope — GJS's module scope makes them directly available to the template without any `import` or `helper()` registration.

Use `{{did-insert}}` from `@ember/render-modifiers` to run a function when an element is added to the DOM.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { action } from '@ember/object';
import { didInsert } from '@ember/render-modifiers';

export default class ScoreChart extends Component {
  @action
  initChart(element) {
    // element is the actual DOM node
    const ctx = element.getContext('2d');
    this.chart = new Chart(ctx, {
      type: 'bar',
      data: {
        labels: this.args.overs.map(o => `Over ${o.number}`),
        datasets: [{ label: 'Runs', data: this.args.overs.map(o => o.runs) }]
      }
    });
  }

  <template>
    <div class="p-4">
      <canvas
        width="600"
        height="300"
        {{didInsert this.initChart}}
      ></canvas>
    </div>
  </template>
}
```

`{{didInsert}}` passes the DOM element as the first argument to your callback. Use it for third-party library initialization that requires a real DOM node.

Use `{{willDestroy}}` from `@ember/render-modifiers` to run cleanup when an element is removed from the DOM.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { action } from '@ember/object';
import { didInsert, willDestroy } from '@ember/render-modifiers';

export default class LiveTicker extends Component {
  intervalId = null;

  @action
  startTicker(element) {
    this.intervalId = setInterval(() => {
      element.textContent = new Date().toLocaleTimeString();
    }, 1000);
  }

  @action
  stopTicker() {
    clearInterval(this.intervalId);
    this.intervalId = null;
  }

  <template>
    <div class="font-mono text-sm text-gray-500 flex items-center gap-2">
      <span class="text-red-500">🔴 LIVE</span>
      <span
        {{didInsert this.startTicker}}
        {{willDestroy this.stopTicker}}
      ></span>
    </div>
  </template>
}
```

Always pair `{{didInsert}}` with `{{willDestroy}}` whenever you create timers, subscriptions, or event listeners to avoid memory leaks.

Bind boolean attributes using `attributeName={{booleanExpression}}` — Glimmer handles truthy/falsy correctly.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ScoreSubmitForm extends Component {
  @tracked isSubmitting = false;

  @action
  async submit() {
    this.isSubmitting = true;
    await this.args.onSubmit();
    this.isSubmitting = false;
  }

  <template>
    <form class="space-y-3">
      <input
        type="number"
        class="border rounded px-3 py-2 w-full"
        disabled={{this.isSubmitting}}
        placeholder="Enter runs"
      />
      <button
        type="button"
        class="w-full py-2 bg-green-600 text-white rounded disabled:opacity-50"
        disabled={{this.isSubmitting}}
        {{on "click" this.submit}}
      >
        Submit Score
      </button>
    </form>
  </template>
}
```

When the bound value is `false` or `undefined`, Glimmer removes the attribute entirely from the DOM — matching native HTML boolean attribute behavior.

Use the `style` attribute with a string value or the `{{concat}}` helper for dynamic styles.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';

export default class ProgressBar extends Component {
  get widthStyle() {
    const pct = Math.min(100, Math.max(0, this.args.percentage ?? 0));
    return `width: ${pct}%`;
  }

  <template>
    <div class="w-full bg-gray-200 rounded-full h-4 overflow-hidden">
      <div
        class="h-4 bg-green-500 transition-all duration-500 rounded-full"
        style={{this.widthStyle}}
      ></div>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-1">{{@percentage}}% complete</p>
  </template>
}
```

Compute the style string in a getter and bind it with `style={{this.widthStyle}}`. Glimmer sanitizes style values to prevent XSS. Prefer Tailwind utility classes when possible and reserve inline styles for truly dynamic values like widths or colors from data.

Use `{{if}}` or `{{concat}}` inside the `class` attribute to conditionally apply classes.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';

export default class TabButton extends Component {
  <template>
    <button
      type="button"
      class={{concat
        "px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium border-b-2 transition-colors "
        (if @isActive
          "border-green-600 text-green-700"
          "border-transparent text-gray-500 hover:text-gray-700"
        )
      }}
      {{on "click" @onClick}}
    >
      {{@label}}
    </button>
  </template>
}
```

The `concat` helper joins strings together in the template. Use `{{if condition "class-a" "class-b"}}` for binary class switching. For many conditions, compute a class string in a getter on the class and bind it as `class={{this.buttonClass}}`.

