In GJS, imported components are directly in scope for the template — no registration or `components` hash needed. The import path follows standard Node.js/ESM conventions.

Import the helper function at the top of the file and call it directly in the template.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { formatDate } from '../helpers/format-date';
import { truncate } from '../helpers/truncate';

export default class ArticleCard extends Component {
  <template>
    <article class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow p-4 space-y-2">
      <time class="text-xs text-gray-400">
        {{formatDate @article.publishedAt "dd MMM yyyy"}}
      </time>
      <h2 class="font-bold text-gray-900">
        {{truncate @article.title 80}}
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">{{@article.summary}}</p>
    </article>
  </template>
}
```

Helpers imported into a GJS file are plain JavaScript functions. Call them in the template using `{{helperName arg1 arg2}}` or with named args using `(helperName arg1 arg2)` in nested expression context.

Use the `{{hash}}` helper to create a plain object with named keys directly in the template.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import PlayerCard from './player-card';

export default class BattingOrder extends Component {
  <template>
    <div class="space-y-2">
      {{#each @players as |player|}}
        <PlayerCard
          @player={{player}}
          @config={{hash
            showStrikeRate=true
            showBalls=true
            compact=false
          }}
        />
      {{/each}}
    </div>
  </template>
}
```

`{{hash key=value}}` creates a plain JavaScript object. This is useful for passing configuration objects to child components without creating a getter on the class. Inside the child, access it as `@config.showStrikeRate`.

Use `{{fn}}` to partially apply arguments to a function, creating a new callable with the args pre-bound.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class OutcomeSelector extends Component {
  @tracked selected = null;

  @action
  selectOutcome(outcome) {
    this.selected = outcome;
    this.args.onChange?.(outcome);
  }

  <template>
    <div class="flex gap-2 flex-wrap">
      {{#each (array "4" "6" "W" "0" "1" "2" "3") as |outcome|}}
        <button
          type="button"
          class="w-10 h-10 rounded-full font-bold text-sm
            {{if (eq this.selected outcome)
              'bg-green-600 text-white'
              'bg-gray-100 text-gray-700 hover:bg-gray-200'
            }}"
          {{on "click" (fn this.selectOutcome outcome)}}
        >
          {{outcome}}
        </button>
      {{/each}}
    </div>
  </template>
}
```

`(fn this.selectOutcome outcome)` creates a new function that calls `selectOutcome` with `outcome` pre-filled. This avoids creating a new `@action` for every iteration.

Use the `{{get}}` helper to look up an object property using a dynamic key.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class StatsViewer extends Component {
  @tracked activeMetric = 'runs';

  statLabels = {
    runs: 'Total Runs',
    wickets: 'Wickets Taken',
    catches: 'Catches',
    strikeRate: 'Strike Rate',
  };

  <template>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm">
        {{get this.statLabels this.activeMetric}}
      </p>
      <p class="text-3xl font-bold text-green-700">
        {{get @playerStats this.activeMetric}}
      </p>
    </div>
  </template>
}
```

`{{get object key}}` is equivalent to `object[key]` in JavaScript. It's essential when the property name is itself a dynamic value stored in state or args.

Use Ember's built-in `<Input>` component with `@value` and `@onChange` for two-way binding.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class SearchPlayers extends Component {
  @tracked query = '';
  @tracked results = [];

  @action
  updateQuery(event) {
    this.query = event.target.value;
    this.args.onSearch?.(this.query);
  }

  <template>
    <div class="relative">
      <input
        type="search"
        class="w-full pl-10 pr-4 py-2 border rounded-lg focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-green-500"
        placeholder="Search players..."
        value={{this.query}}
        {{on "input" this.updateQuery}}
      />
      <span class="absolute left-3 top-2.5 text-gray-400">🔍</span>
      {{#if this.query}}
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Searching for: {{this.query}}</p>
      {{/if}}
    </div>
  </template>
}
```

In GJS, use a native `<input>` with `{{on "input" handler}}` for text inputs rather than Ember's `<Input>` component — it gives you full control and works better with Tailwind. Update the tracked property in the handler from `event.target.value`.

